{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689937/1958060901/0441.xml":{"full_text":"Key West, Florida, has the\nmost equable climate In the\ncountry, with an average\nrange of only 14*Jghrenhelt\nVOL. Ne.\nSheriff Begins Crack-Down On Bolita\nU.S. \u2019Copter Held\nWrangle\nSeen On\nPrisoners'\nBERLIN (AP))\u2014Russia refused\ntoday to take responsibility for the\nnine U.S. Army men taken pris\noner by the East german Com\nmunists Saturday when their hel\nicopter made a forced landing in\nside the satellite.\nKeeping up its campaign to\nforce Western recognition of the\npuppet Communist government,\nthe Russian embassy in East Ber\nlin declared that the East German\nregime has jurisdiction over the\nAmerican prisoners and their air\neraft because the helicopter came\ndown outside the three Allied air\ncorridors to West Berlin.\nRussia guarantees free Allied\nair traffic through these corridors\nunder a 1949 Big Four agreement.\nThe Soviet embassy statement\nindicated the United States and\nRussia were heading into a big\ndiplomatie wrangle over the nine\nAmericans.\nThe Russian statment was in re\nsponse to a newsman\u2019s question\nwhether Russia or East Germany\nhad jurisdiction over the Ameri\ncans.\nEarlier the East German gov\nerametn claimed it has the right\nto say what will be done with\nMio helicopter and those aboard it.\n\u25a0ft* United States does not rec-\nMBjN |he East German Commu\naU regime and had demanded\nthat the Soviets M East Berlin\npromptly return the eight Army\noMtors, one sergeant and their\naircraft.\nThe Western Allies contend that\nhi accordance with the postwar\nfour-power agreements on Ger\nmany, all their dealings concern\ning East Germany must bo with\nthe Soviet Union.\nThe helicopter belonged to the\nSrd Armored Division and had\nbeen on a military exercise. U. S.\nauthorities assumed the craft\nturned east due to a navigational\nerror in a thunderstorm and ran\nout of gas.\nR came down at Zwickau, 30\nmiles east of the border. The So\nviet army headquarters in East\nBerlin said all nine men were safe\nand unharmed.\nThe East German Foreign Min\nistry announced it had sent the\nU. S. State Department a note\nprotesting that East German air\nspace had been violated. The For\neign Ministry followed up today\nwith a declaration that the fact\nit had sent its protest direct to\nthe State Department showed the\nEast German regime and not the\nSoviet*\u2014has jurisdiction in the\nA Belgian jet fighter was farced\ndown in East Germany 12 days\nago. The Soviets have referred all\nBelgian queries to the East Ger*\nmans.\nThe Americans still refused to\nannounce the names of the nine\nmen in the helicopter, contending\nthat all the next-of-kin had not\nbeen notified. The Army did con\nfirm an East German report that\none of the passengers was Maj.\nJames Zeller, artillery training of\nficer of the 3rd Armored Division.\nZeller\u2019s home town was not given.\nThe East German spokesman\nrefused to say where the men\nwere now or when they might be\nreleased.\nTrain For Regcue Of Americans In Trouble Spots\nU.S. 6th Fleet Gathers In Med.\nWITH U. S. 6TH FLEET. Off Di\nkili, Turkey (AP>\u2014Major units of\nthis mighty Mediterranean fleet\nassembled off the Turkish coast\ntoday .to train in rescuing Ameri\ncans from the turbulent countries\nof the Middle East.\nThe heavily armed amphibious\nforce of Marines, backed up by\nsailors and naval airmen, are\npracticing for duty they might\nface at any moment.\nIf the crisis deepened in Leba\nnon, only 12 hours steaming to\nthe south, the united force could\nswitch from training to the real\nthinr\n(thr Keg West\nTHE SOUTHERNMOST NEWSPAPER IN THE U.S.A.\nCRASH INJURIS ACTRISS\u2014Here Is the demolished station wagon in which movie actress Stay\nParker, 25, was-ln|urod and her father, George L. Parker, 43, was killed Saturday when It was\nstruck by a Florida last Coast freight train aix miles south of St. Augustine mar Vermont Heights.\n\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nGains Reported In State Economy\nCautious Optimism\nAdvised By Collins\nTALLAHASSEE (APD-A slow\nly rising economy in Florida that\n\u2022will pick up speed in the fall and\nreturn to normal about the end of\nthe year is forecast by Gov. Col\nlins.\nAssessing the state's business\nfuture for The Associated Press,\nCollins said:\n\u201cThere io reason to be cautious\nly optimistic about the business\noutlook for Florida during the re\nmainder of 1958.\n\"The bad effects of our severe\nwinter have now largely run their\ncourse, and the national business\nrecession shows signs of bottom\ning out. There are indications of\na record summer and fall season\nwhich wiO recoup some of thia\npast winter\u2019s losses.\"\nThe governor said Florida's 1958\ntourist business should approxi\nmate the previous year.\n\"This year may be the first in\nmany not to show an appreciable\nincrease in total number of tour\nist and tourist income. However,\nthis summer promises to be a\nrecord season. Airline reservations\ntr Florida are up 20 per cent and\nrailroad tours to Florida are up\n10 per cent,\u201d Collins said.\nNonagricultural employment in\nFlorida in April was slightly\nahead of the estimate a year ago,\nin contrast to a decline nationally,\nCollins said.\nLots Of Prospects\nBEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (API\nDan Greenhouse advertised\nhis three-bedroom, three-bath hill\ntop home with swimming pool and\nview of the ocean for rent at $l,-\n000 a month. Only the ad in the\nnewspaper came out $lOO. \"What\na weekend,\u201d he sighed. \"The\nphone's been ringing ever since\nthe ad appeared.\u201d\nThe fleet is currently reinforced\nby 18 ships over the usual 50 and\nby double the usual complement\nof 1,800 Marines.\nAt dawn, transports, warships\nand landing ships maneuvered\naround the Greek island off Les\nbos for a landing near Dikili.\nThe amphibious task force was\nbacked up by the cruiser Des\nMoines, the Bth Fleet\u2019s flagship,\nits sister ship the Salem and a\nscreen of destroyers to give gun\nfire support.\nFarther out to sea lay the ear\nners Saratoga and Essex to lend\nHe said manufacturing employ\nment declined 3 per cent from a\nyear ago, due to curtailed citrus\ncanneries\u2019 production. But, he\nadded, production of electric pow\ner was up 18 per cent in January,\ncompare to a slight decline na\ntionally.\nRetail sales for April were sub\nstantially ahead of a year ago, he\nsaid.\nHigher prices will increase the\ncitrus industry\u2019s income about 10\nper cent this year. Collins said,\nalthough some individual growers\nsuffered severe freeze losses.\nWinter vegetable damage was\nheavy, but the rest of the state\u2019s\nagricultur suffered little or no\nloss. Net farm income for 1958\nprobably will exceed that of last\nyear, the governor said.\nCollins said the sales and ciga\nrette taxes showed substantial\nSupertanker Hits Fishing Trawler\nShip Collision Is\nNews To Tanker C.O.\nPROVINCETOWN, Mass. fAP)\n\u2014A tanker and a fishing vessel\ncollided 12 miles off the tip of\nCape Cod yesterday but the skip\nper of the tanker was unaware\nof it for two hours.\nThe captain of the fishing trawl\ner Yankee said the supertanker\nJamestown \"kept right on going\nafter the collision.\u201d\nA Coast Guard spokesman at\nBoston said that about two hours\nafter the crash the Jamestown\nquestioned by radio whether a\nair cover with nearly 200 planes\n\u2014including jets capable of carry\ning nuclear bombs.\nA third qgrrier, the Wasp, was\npart of the* reinforcements. It car\nried heliqppters for Marine land\nings five/miles inland.\nOne of the day\u2019s problems was\nto establish a beachhead on two\nmiles of coast and control an area\nwithin a 25-mile radius by artil\nlery, planes and gunfire.\nAfter the exercise, the bulk of\nthe fleet leaves' for a visit to\nGreek and Turkish ports still\nonly about a day\u2019s forced sailing\nfrom smouldering Lebanon.\nKIY WIST, FLORIDA, MONDAY, JUNI 9,19 M\ngains in April, reversing a drop\noff that started last October.\n\u201cBank deposits and bank loans\nhave started to turn up. This does\nnot indicate a rapid business re\ncovery within the next few months,\nbut it docs tend to support a very\nslow rise during the summer\nmonths, gathering momentum in\nthe fall, with an expected return\nto normal around the end of the\nyear.\n\"The large part of the dollar in\ncrease in state revenue will not\nbe realized until the first six\nmonths of 1959, since the state re\nceives roughly 65 per cent of its\nrevenue in the last t<B quarters\nof any fiscal year.\n\"This means that the major por\ntion of Florida\u2019s 1958-59 revenue\nwill be collected after the econ\nomy has made its expected return\nto normal,\u201d Collins said.\nvessel had overturned off Race\nPoint.\nThe Coast Guard advised the\nJamestown of the accident and\nasked the tanker\u2019s skipper to re\nport the incident at his destina\ntion, Harbor Island, Tex.\nCapt. Arthur Duarte, 55, skip\nper of the 60-foot fishing craft,\nbattled for three hours with his\ntwo-man crew to keep the vessel\nafloat and bring her into port.\nThe Yankee's bilge pump kept\njust ahead of the ocean pouring\ninto the fishing vessel\u2019s holds\nthrough a hole near the stern and\nthrough open deck seams.\nThe 206-foot, 1,538 gross ton\nJamestown, an Esso Oil Co. ship\nbased at Wilmington, Del., appar\nently was not damaged.\nCapt. Duarte and his crewmen,\nArthur Joseph, 63, and Antone\nHenrique, 60, all of Provincetown,\nI brought their vessel to port under\nher own power while a Coast\nGuard vessel stood by.\nCapt. Duart esaid, \"Hie weath\ner was very, very clear. We\ncouldn\u2019t believe it when we looked\nup. It was like a mountain rolling\ndown on top of us. It was only 110\nfeet away. I kept blowing my\nwhistle.\n\"A crewman on the deck of the\nJamestown looked down and\nyelled \u2018What\u2019s the matter?\u2019 But\nthe tanker didn\u2019t even alow down.\u201d\nMenshikov Issues Statement\nRed Diplomat\nDenies Guilt\nWASHINGTON (AP) Soviet\nAmbassador Mikhail Menshikov\nsays a junior Soviet diplomat de\nnies trying to buy American mili\ntary secrets. AH Russians in this\ncountry, Memhikov says, are for\nbidden to do anything improper.\nMenshikov told a TV panel that\nNikolai I. Kurochkin, the Soviet\nEmbassy\u2019s third secretary, has\ndenied State Department charges\nthat he sought to purchase secret\nmilitary documents from Charles\nT. Beaumet, an American maga\nzine writer.\n\u201cAnd I have no reason not to\nbelieve him,\u201d Menshikov said.\nKurochkin was ordered Satur-\nBeauty Isn\u2019t\nImpaired In\nAuto Crash\nST. AUGUSTINE, Fla. (AP)\nSuzy Parker\u2019s physician says the\n25-year-old actress is still a very\nbeautiful girl despite injuries in\na train-auto crash. Two arms\nwere broken but her face was un\nmarked ta the accident Saturday\nnight.\nThe crash kile^het Mier.\nMias Parker was to\nthe hospital under the name of\nMrs. Pierre Lasalle of New York\nCity. It was the first public dis\nclosure that she was married.\nLasalle arrived fa St Augustine\nfrom New York last night to be\nat her aide. Newamen could not\nreach him for comment. A mem\nber of the family dedined to say\nhow long they had been married.\nThe accident occurred when\nMiss Parker and her father\nGeorge Lofton Parker, 60, were\ndriving to Jacksonville after visit\ning her mother in the hospital\nhere. Mrs. Parker is recovering\nfrom a recent operation.\nA state trooper said Parker,\nowner of Parker Printing Prepa\nrations in Jacksonville, apparent\nly did not see or hear the Florida\nEast Coast Railway train ap\nproach a crossing.\nMiss Parker\u2019s physician said\nshe will be hospitalized for sev\neral weeks.\nMiss Packer, a former top New\nYork model, has had roles in two\nmovies, \"Kiss Them for Me\u201d with\nGary Grant and Jayne Mansfield\nand \"10 North Frederick\u201d with\nGary Cooper.\nKelly Women\nAsk Freedom\nOKLAHOMA CITY (API- Two\nprison-pale women, the widow and\nmother-in-law of George (Machine\nGun) Kelly, plead today for re\nlease after 25 years of confine\nment.\nTheir petition to U.S. District\nCourt alleges that they received\nan unfair trial and subsequent life\nsentences for their part In the 1933\nkidnaping of Oklahoma City oil\nman Charles Urschel, now of San\nAntonio, Tex.\nMrs. Kathryn KeUy, M, and her\nwidowed mother Mrs. Ora Shan\nnon, 70, were brought here Satur\nday night from the federal wom\nen\u2019s prison at Alderson, W.Va.\nKelly, a onetime public enemy,\ndied in the Leavenworth, Kan.,\nfederal prison three years ago.\nMrs. Shannon's husband R. G.\nShannon served time in prison but\nwas released because of ill health.\nHe died at his farm near Para\ndise, Tex., where Urschel was\nheld for $200,000 ransom and freed\nunharmed.\nJames G. Laughlin, Washington,\nD.C., attorney representing the\nwomen, contended in his petition\nthat the women received an un\nfair trial because of a feeling cre\nated by publicity. It was the first\ntrial under the Lindbergh Act,\nwhich brought such crimes under\nday to leave the United States on\ngrounds be paid hundreds of dol\nlars for Anny manuals and other\nmaterials and tried to get secret\ndocuments. He is expected to start\nfor home later this week.\nBeaumet, a 25-year-old maga\nzir\u00bb' writer living in nearby Ar-\n\u201e-on, Va., said he never gave\nny classified information to the\nRussian. Beaumet said he\nfurnished Kurochkin some non\nsecret material, part of which\n\u201cwas already in the papers.\u201d For\nthis, Beaumet said, he received\n1435 over a period of months,\nstarting last year.\nJustice Department officials\nsaid Beaumet cooperated with\ngovernment investigators after\nthey questioned him about his\ntransactions with Kurochkin. Of\nficials said Beaumet since has re\ngistered as a foreign agent and\nthat the department planned no\naction against him.\nThe move to oust Kurochkin for\n\"highly improper activities\u201d came\nabout three weeks after the Soviet\nUnion had expelled John A. Baker\nJr., second secretary of the U, S.\nEmbassy in Moscow. Baker, 30,\nwas accused of violating what the\nSoviets called \"the norms of be\nhavior\u201d for diplomats. The United\nStates has disputed the accusation\nagainst Baker.\nIn an Interview Saturday night,\nBeaumet said he met Kurochkin\nlast year after he went to the\nSoviet Embassy seeking material\nYara story An thTmakihg of stock\ntags in the Soviet Union. At the\ntme, Beaumet said, he was do\ning free-lance work for a textile\nindustry publication.\nLater, Beaumet said, Kurochkin\ninvited him to a party at the\nSoviet Embassy and that subse\nquently he got the material bp\nwanted from Moscow.\nAbout five months later. Beau\nmet said, he lunched with the Rus\nsian, who he said suggested they\ncollaborate on some articles for\nSoviet publications. At this time,\nBeaumet said he was working for\nthe National Guardsman maga\nzine. That magazine has said it\ndischarged Beaumet for immature\njudgment.\nTwo Methodist\nPastors To Move\nTwo of the Methodist ministers\nserving here have been assigned\nto new churches, according to in\nformation from the annual con\nference held in Lakeland last\nweek.\nThe Rev. Charles H. Ketchum,\npastor of the Fleming Street Me\nthodist Church for the past two\nyears, has been assigned to the\nBelleview Church In the Gaines\nville District.\nThe Rev. J. W. Blitch, who has\nserved the Ley Memorial Church\nfor the past three years, was as\nsigned to the Avondale Church\nin Jacksonville.\nThe Rev. L. E. Watkins has\nbeen assigned to the Fleming\nStreet Church for the coming\nyear and the Rev. W. A. Wicker\nwill serve Ley Memorial.\nSmuggled Goods Nosed Out\nExpert Coffee Cop\nBONN, Germany The\nWest German government is\nwarmly applauding one of its\nfemale customs officials for out\nstanding achievement in nosing\nout coffee smugglers.\nThe attractive brunette, fondly\ncalled Geisha by her colleagues,\nhas built up a reputation as the\nmost efficient coffee cop along the\nDutch-German border.\n\"It is thanks to Geisha,\u201d said\nthe official government gazette,\n\u201cthat almost no illicit coffee now\ncrosses the border she patrols.\u201d\nBeing a specially trained 214-\nyear-old spaniel, Geisha just puts\nher wet, curious nose up in the air\nand follows the coffee scent.\nShe never fails. She has located\ncoffee buried under loads ft coal.\n27 Arrested In Two Raids\nAs County Clean-up Starts\nBy DINIS SNIIM\nSheriff John Spottiwood\u2019g department cracked\ndown on bolita and gambling Saturday night, arresting\ntwo white men and 25 Negroes in two raids.\nSix persons were charged with possession of bolita\ntickets and with gambling. The others were charged\n-i only with gambling.\nvj 3\ni\nWra\n1 B\n\nI\n\nLOMBARDO lUYS\u2014Guy Lom\nbardo has announced that ha 1s\nbuying the Shamrock Restau\nrant and Key Colony Beach\nClub from F. F. \"Phil\" Sadow\nski for an undisclosed amount.\nThe announcement come Sun\nday during the famed orchestra\nleader's appearance for a\ndame. Lombardo said negotia\ntions for the purchase had been\ncompleted.\u2014Citizen Staff Photo,\nDon Finder.\nMacmillan\nAsks Closer\nEconomic Ties\nINDIANAPOLIS (API- British\nPrime Minister Harold Macmillan\nappealed yesterday for closer ec\nonomic ties between his country\nand the United States.\nIn a nationally televised com\nmencement address at De Pauw\nUniversity at Greencastle, Ind.,\nthe Prime Minister said, \"There\nare still too many artificial bar\nriers to the free flow of money\nand trade in the free world.\u201d\nNow that \"we all face a com\nmon danger,\" Macmillan said, in\nterdependence must be the \"key\nnote of the second half of the 20th\ncentury it the progress of human\nity is to continue.\u201d\nThe Prime Minister goes by\nplane today to Washington for an\ninformal conference with Presi\ndent Eisenhower and Secretary of\nState John Foster Dulles.\nIn a 2labour sweep through In\ndiana official and social affairs,\nMacmillan emphasised these\nthings:\n1. He considers Gen. Charles de\nGaulle, France\u2019s new premier, a\nfriend and hopes France will\nsolve many of its problems under\nDe Gaulle\u2019s leadership.\n2. \"Prosperity is not indivisible;\nthere are too many artificial bar\nriers to the free flow of money\nand trade in the free world.\u201d\n3. Russians are \"very intelligent\n(Continued on Page Four)\nwrapped in petrol-soaked cloths,\nand in all the unlikely places\nsmugglers and unbelieving cus\ntoms officials can think of. The\ngovernment gazette describes\nher as \"one of the most active\nand reliable customs officials in\nthe employ of the federal repub\nlic.\u201d\nWith the duty on coffee about 50\ncents a pound, the beverage has\nbeen one of the smugglers\u2019 favor\nite items. Geisha is one of only\ntwo dogs in the entire West Ger\nman customs service trained to\ntrack down the fragrant contra\nband.\nFrequently she is taken aboard\nborder-crossing Rhine vessels and\non to international freight and\npassenger trains. She invariably\nlocates undeclared coffee.\nw Miner aunmiary\nContinued partly cloudy. Show\ners. Low tonight, 75 to 79. High\nTuesday, 84. Tomorow\u2019s tides:\nHigh, 4:38 a. m., I p. m. Low,\n11:03 a. m., 10:38 p. m. Winds\nE to SE gentle to moderate.\nFRICI FIVI CINTB\nTen uniformed deputies,\nled by Capt. Sidney Curry\nand Lt. Rene Raiole, raided\nthe Peach Pool Room, 731\nWhitehead St. and the Hi*\nHat Club, 409 Petronia, at\n10 p.m. Saturday.\nSheriff Spottswood, in a strongly\nworded statement today, made it\ndear that his department was\nout to elean up\u2019 gambling and\nbolita where ever it is found both\nin Key West and in the county.\nThe following were charged\nwith gambling and possession\nof bolita tickets.\nFred Tate, 38, Negro, 8181 k\nTerry Lane, H. Roberts, 65, Ne\ngro, 809 Terry Lane, Will Chis\nholm, 63, Negro, 407 Petronia,\nGrover Pless, 38, Negro, 824\nWhitehead, Frank Being, 47, No\ngro, 827 Emma, 8. Edwards, 65,\nNegro, 719 Elizabeth.\nHie following were charged\nwith gambling:\nEthel Robinson, >4, Negro, 714\nEmms; Elizabeth Scott, 52, Ne.\ngro. Whitehead; Ruth Taylor, 24,\nNegro, 310 NW 18th Terrace, Mi\nami; Henry Poole, <l3, Negro,\n228 Mick\u00ae. Lane; Stephen Pla,\n40, Noire, 904 Terry Lane;\nLeroy Jordan, 38, Negro, 822\nWhitehead; Terry Thomas, 46, No.\ngro, 423 Olivia; Johnny C. Wil\nliams, 39, Negro, 110 Julia; Duke\nButler, 50, Negro, 2-D Art Vil\nlage; John Roberts, 84, Negro,\n900 Thomas;\nJoe Davis, 52, Negro, 320 Bap\ntist Lane; Alfred Kemp, 67, 824\nWhitehead; Ohio Harris, 45 Ne\ngro, 1025 Thomas; Carl Saunders,\n29, Negro, 628 Mickens Lane;\nJohnny Walton, 58, Negro. 703\nElizabeth;\nPaul Kennon, 47, Negro, 211\nVirginia; Miguel Pazo, 59, White,\n818 Olivia: Fernando Gato, 69,\nWhite, 1108 Grinnell; J. A Rod\nriguez, 59, White, 904 Duval;\nLloyd Stallworth, 54, Negro, 311\nPetronii; Rannie Bunc, 27, Ne\ngro, 810 Thomas.\nIn response to requests from\nthe press for comment on the\ngambling raids Spottswood said:\n\"Frankly, I thought' I made it\nvery clear in my press release\nof June 5, 1958. At that time I\nstated that the Governor request\ned that we make Bolita, which\nof course includes all gambling,\nour Number One project.\n\"With limited personnel it is\nimpossible for us to raid all sus\npected places at once but I can\nassure all concerned that no\nplace or operation suspected of\nviolating the gambling laws of\nthe State of Florida will be omit\nted from our itinerary.\n\u2022The gambling laws ct Florida\nmay be found in Chapter 849 cl\nthe Florida Statues. Therein one\nwill find that whoever plays or\nengages at any game of cards,\nroulette, lottery, operates or uses\na slot machine or device for gam\nbling. engages in or has in his\npossession baseball tips, etc., lot\ntery tickets, bolita ticiets etc\u2019,\nare in violation of the laws of\nFlorida,\n\"All personnel of the Sheriffs\nDepartment have been instructed\nto make arrests for all violations\nof the gambling laws of Florida.\n\u201cDuval Street from water\nto water would do well to rid\nitself of any semblance of gamb\nling as we intend to make the\nstreet what it is intended to be\nthe main street of the City of\nKey West symbolic of the bus\ninessmen and the type of com\nmunity in which we live.\n\"And by this, I do not mean\nthat we are not going to enforce\nthe gambling laws elsewhere.\u201d\nWar Dead Remembered\nKYOTO, Japan (AP)\u2014A marble\nmonument to the Allied soldiers\nwho died on Japanese soil in\nWorld War II was dedicated Sun\nday at the base of the Buddhist\nstatue to Japan\u2019s own war dead.","height":"29373","width":"21043"}}
